I was a teenager when I first saw someone lose their glasses at a concert. It was actually a “show,” not a “concert.” Smaller venue, standing room only. I don’t remember the punk rock band I was watching but I remember this. A circle pit was having its way with the audience when I saw a kid grabbing at his face saying he lost his glasses. He went searching. My heart sank. I dove under the crowd, the sweat, the boots, the sound, and helped him find his now broken pair of spectacles. Feeling the tug on our shirts, we were launched back to our feet by others as he yelled over the music, “it’s ok! Thanks, I’m good!” 

At the beginning of this year I went back to weekly volunteering with @visionsvcb after the pandemic robbed many of us from our natural instinct to care for one another. Years ago I participated in programs with them and had to pause to build my business. I was eager to return. 

Inspired by so many things but mainly my retired Uncle, whose done various volunteer jobs for decades from checking people in at an ER, to equine therapy, and literally holding drug-addicted new born babies in the hospital. (Sorry ladies, he’s taken) 

It was an interesting route to get to working with the visually impaired. You all know me, topically, visually. You pepper me with questions on my style, look, and taste. When bonding with the blind, this is a nonissue. I’m seen without being seen. After all, my time spent with them is not about me. It’s about them. A truly unselfish act that ironically fulfills myself.

“Good Vibes Only”? What a waste of neon. You could pick any original phrase to sell the cool factor of a shop and this is it? It’s like when I hear a guitarist on the subway playing Hotel California. Do you work for a karaoke bar down here?! You’re an unsigned artist. You can pick ANY song you want and you’re blowing it on Hotel California?!! 😵‍💫😵‍💫😵‍💫

While we’re at it, why so modest? Go bigger. Go better. How about “Great Vibes Only”? Screw it, “BEST Vibes Only.” The BEST vibes ONLY will be tolerated in this space. Not good. Not great. THE BEST. When you order your coffee, it better be the BEST order ever! We want singing, dancing, cartwheels, balloon animals, real animals, jazz hands, no hands, high fives, swan dives, five guys in thigh highs! Go crazy, this is BEST. VIBES. ONLY. 

#merrychristmas
As the great Jack Skellington once said, “Well….I may as well give them what they want.” ✨🧥

FOR THE SAKE OF TIME 

I was with a group of friends, clad in vintage attire, when a woman ran up to us. “Wow, why are you dressed like that?!” She looked slack-jawed, as the words bounced from her lips like big fun on the bayou and without missing a beat, I replied “we’re coming from a birthday party.” 

This was not true. We were not “coming from a birthday party.” However, it provided the reaction I’ve longed for over the years when a stranger turns into a vampire coming to suck my time. 

“Ohh, nice!” she replied, smiled and walked away. We would be gone by the time she realized my response made no sense. However, it gave everyone what they wanted. She did get an answer….maybe not the one she hoped for but what would that have been anyway? Her first trip to the Big Apple and she was expecting to meet a real life group of time traveling secret agents disguised as civilians sent to protect New York from the evil, Dr. Future?!

I got what I wanted as well. My time back. I do not care to explain the minutiae of my dressings to total strangers in passing. I have friends who’ll stop, thank them for their question, begin to describe who we are, what we like, etc.. But why? Someone’s about to ask that very same question 10 blocks from now! 

In these situations, my goal is to give a response that warrants no more questions. All the time, every time, for the sake of time.
I always wanted to be a cartoon. 📸 @stevenrosenphoto

Maybe my interior design and architect friends can explain why I’m in love with the apartment in 2017’s “The Shape of Water.” I melt into my own puddle every time I see this room. 

The cool tones of the blue and green…🧘‍♂️ The diagonally crossed floor boards. Hokusai’s Great Wave 🌊 imbedded into the wall, awash in layers of peeling paint stains it fades into the subconscious. The window sill and arch, 🤤 inspired by 1948’s The Red Shoes! The kitchen table (which mirrors my own vintage set in matching shade) or the humor in a vacuum cleaner, since Elisa has no carpets. The drippy rainy stains on the glass just bring peace and calm to my every muscle! 

How does Del Toro do it?! How does Sally Hawkins do it?! Maybe she’s a siren, maybe she’s a muse, maybe she’s born with it, maybe it’s Maybeline!

Thinking about how much fun dancing is and how much I love being in motion! As an antsy child, It was always an uphill battle when it came to sitting still, staying focused, staying quiet. I’ve learned to do the latter two but I still gotta move a bit otherwise I melt like a stick a butter in the sun. 

Dancing calms my body and mind. I feel like I cruise through my days with a bit of grease and glide. I’m always thinking a sentence ahead of the one that comes out of my mouth. I’m always picturing the space I occupy before I physically land there. 

If you’ve got a loud mind and natural bubbling energy, put it to positive use.

There is something about “Happy Hour” and it’s relentless pitching that turns me off. I think it could be changed to “Content Hour.” After all, happiness seems a lot for people to live up to, but “Content!” Now that’s something achievable! Content is attainable. Affordable. It’s modest. It’s realistic. It’s not showy and it never lets you down. Your neighbor is content. Your turtle is content! 

“Happy” seems assuming, even for an hour. I like to approach everyone as if they’re grieving (because I’m pretty sure they are in some way or another..) 

Visible happiness causes skepticism. Have you ever had a person with a shaved head, robe, & story, saunter up to hand you a flower in public? Have you ever encountered a man climbing out of a subway tunnel with smiling laughter so loud it rattles the rails with 10,000 years of insanity? 

I really think “Content Hour” is the way to go. I trust it. I could get behind it for the communal happiness of everyone around me.

Happy Passover! 

📸 @kazkoltai

(An excerpt from my writing on naps..) 
There’s an art to the public nap. They say Thomas Edison was ruthless & stole others inventions but what that has to do with napping, I’ll never know. I’ve napped on planes, trains, & automobiles. I’ve napped in corners of crowded bars, loud parties, & apparently on a bed of strangers coats & bags. One day I hope to teach this art to my closest family members. They can be my napkins.

This 1950’s, one & only, cotton terry cloth paisley cabana set has a story. The vintage dealer I got it from explained how she acquired the matching set from a Jewish family in The Bronx. The family’s grandfather was a tailor… in German-occupied Europe during WW2. In short, his skill of being a tailor with “fast hands” kept him alive during the war. After he escaped and settled in NYC, he opened a tailor shop. Sometimes he would be commissioned to create a custom piece that its future owner never picked up for whatever reason. This cabana set was one of those pieces. Years & trends passed and the original family kept it, along with other garments, stored safely. I’ll do the same. After I dance in it. @viva.las.vegas.vlv

When I was a child I had two imaginary friends, “Jimmy” and “Johnny.” Yes, even my imaginary friends had old-timey names and yes, in typical only child fashion, I selfishly demanded TWO of everything— Including imaginary friends! 

They say only children tend to be maladjusted, independent, sarcastic, private, and strive for perfectionism. All foreign concepts to me. 😎

When my peers were pouring over computer games and cars, I kept to myself, perfecting self-entertainment such as Devil Sticks, Tech decks, Yo-Yo, Comedy, Magic, and of course, Juggling. I cherish these skills to this day. They gave me a creative outlet, challenged me and made me the most popular kid in school, even if only to “Jimmy” and “Johnny.”
